\begin_layout Subsection
Pathophysiology of embryonic hearts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cardiac development is a highly organized process controlled by an evolutionary
 conserved gene regulatory network that interlinks transcription factors
 and signaling pathways with genes for muscle growth, patterning and contraction.
 A set of specific conserved transcription factors (MEF2, Tbx, NK2, GATA
 and Hand) set up the heart development and regulates each other’s expression,
 thereby providing stability to the cardiac gene program
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "14_Vecoli2014,16_Olson2006"

\end_inset

.
 Fetal heart progenitor cells are differentiated into specific lineages
 to form specific types of cells.
 The differentiation of these cells into a particular lineage is a confined
 regulatory process, which is based on the microenvironment and the signaling
 cues in the extracellular matrix.
 Deregulation of the regulatory genes involved in lineage determination,
 differentiation, or cardiac development leads to the fetal heart failure,
 and may also end up in embryonic lethality.
 Inability to contract and malfunctioning of the myocardial compliance as
 a result of hemodynamic stress amplify the incidence of fetal heart failure
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "6_Nandi2015,14_Vecoli2014"

\end_inset

