\begin_layout Standard
DNA is organized in chromatin composed of condensed nucleosomes: units of
 146 bp of DNA wrapped twice around an octamer of two copies of each histone
 protein H2A, H2B, H3, and H4.
 The flexible amino-terminal tails of the histones, protruding outward from
 the nucleosome, allow for post-translational modifications through (de)acethyla
tion, phosporylation, ubiquitination, methylation, and sumoylation.
 Such covalent modifications alter DNA–histone interactions, affecting accessibi
lity of transcription factors.
 Chromatin plays an important role in the regulation of gene expression.
 It is highly structured and can be compacted to varying degrees, which
 impacts on the accessibility of the DNA for the transcription machinery.
 The basic unit of chromatin is the nucleosome, consisting of 146 base pairs
 (bp) of DNA wrapped around eight histone proteins.
 A number of epigenetic mechanisms control the chromatin structure, including
 chromatin remodeling complexes, modifications and variants of histone proteins
 as well as modifications of the DNA itself
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "45_Serra-Juhe2015"

\end_inset

.
 Histones are small globular proteins that are highly conserved and can
 undergo various post-translational modifications, such as methylation,
 acetylation or phosphorylation on their N-terminal tails.
 These modifications act either directly on chromatin structure by altering
 electrostatic charges and thereby internucleosomal contacts or serve as
 targeting signals for chromatin remodeling complexes or other chromatin-binding
 proteins.
 Different modifications can function as activators or repressors of transcripti
on [46, 47].
 Epigenetics is henceforth the amalgamation of all the processes that are
 in charge of the expression of the genes involved in the normal development
 of all tissues and organs including; the DNA sequences that code for structural
 proteins, or those that are responsible for the regulatory proteins such
 as transcription factors
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "31_Kopf2009"

\end_inset

.
 Among the various epigenetic mechanisms, aberrant DNA methylation has been
 distinctly linked to a number of diseases.
 By the addition of a methyl group in the 5′ carbon of cytosine a change
 in the structure of the DNA molecule occurs leading to a wide range of
 possible alterations of gene expression pattern.
 Conclusively, aberrant DNA methylation with its transcriptional consequences
 might have a significant role in causing human disease
