\begin_layout Section
Atrial septal defect (ASD)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Atrial septal defect (ASD) is a congenital cardiac disorder and occurs widely
 in females rather than males, as a result of the spontaneous malformation
 in the interatrial septum / opening in the atrial septum (septa are physical
 extensions of the myocardium lined with endocardium, located between the
 two atria), allowing the blood to transfer directly between the left and
 right atrium.
 Atrial septation is defined as the division of a common atrium into the
 left and right atrium that are noticed in a structurally well-developed,
 four chambered tetrapod heart.
 Adding to this, the atrial septum is developed by three distinct structures
 that undertakes concurrent morphogenesis: the atrioventricular endocardial
 cushions, the primary atrial septum (PAS), and the spina vestibuli or dorsal
 mesenchymal protrusion (SV/DMP)
