\begin_layout Subsection
Embryology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Atrial septation starts in the end of the 4th week Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig16"

\end_inset

.
 From the roof of the atrium, between the systemic and pulmonary venous
 openings a muscular shelf - “septum primum” – grows which later fuses with
 the superior endocardial cushion at the atrioventricular level.
 The interatrial linkage that exists before this fusion is called “ostium
 primum”.
 However, before the closure of the ostium primum, the upper part of the
 primary septum is fragmented down creating a new interatrial communication
 – the “ostium secundum”.
 When the ostium primum is annihilated, the expansion of a posterior structure,
 spina vestibuli, also plays a crucial role.
 It is further encapsulated by muscles, thus making the base of the primary
 septum stronger.
 The upper and thinner part of the fibromuscular primary septum will then
 serve as the flap valve of foramen ovale.
 At this point, the roof of the primary atrium, between the systemic and
 pulmonary venous entrances, initiates unfolding, thereby creates the secondary
 septum –“septum secundum” that will form the upper rims of the foramen
 ovale.
 Still, the secondary septum is not a true septum but rather it is sandwich-like
 in-folding of the atrial wall compiled with extracardiac adipose tissue.
 This interatrial groove is often referred to as Söndergaard’s or Waterston’s
 groove”.
 Atrial septal “lipoma” or “lipomateous hypertrophy” is a common echocardiograph
ic finding and, the denomination proposes involvement of the septum whereas
 it is actually an extracardiac fat.
 By the 12th week of development the right and left pulmonary venous become
 separated and the atrial septation is terminated.
