\begin_layout Subsection
Incidence and causes of ASDs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reported incidence of congenital heart disease varies a lot, /1000 live
 births and there are a number of reasons for this.
 Most studies are merely restricted to infancy or childhood and do not count
 lesions detected later in life.
 This has a significant relevance for ASD, which often is diagnosed in adult
 life.
 Previous studies reporting the highest incidences are characterized by
 a frequent use of echocardiography in a neonatal setting or during infancy
 and, it is thus very obvious that the principal reason for the increase
 of the incidence of CHD reported in recent years is the detection of mild
 forms, particularly small ventricular septal defects.
 Besides, small ASDs of the secundum type are also abundantly found, yet
 it seems that the spontaneous closure rate is higher than formerly thought.
 In addition to the diagnostic methodology and the age profile of the investigat
ed population, referral patterns will play a major role in retrospective
 studies based on a huge population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Resent findings reveals that despite the high prevalence and the significant
 association with substantial morbidity and mortality, the fundamental etiology
 responsible for ASD and majority of cases with it remains unknown..
 The aberrant development of the atrial septum includes heterogeneous complex
 biological processes and identifies important transcription factors involved
 in atrial septation such as Gata4, Nkx2–5 and Tbx5, associated with accurate
 spatial and temporal cooperation of cardiac cells commitment, differentiation
 and proliferation of adhesion molecules, activation and expression of signallin
g molecules, and both environmental and genetic risk factors.
 This may disrupt this natural biological process of cardiogenesis and thus,
 generating a large spectrum of congenital heart defects
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "22_Fahed2013,52_Perloff1995,53_Lutembacher1959"

\end_inset

.
 On the contrary, there are families with recurrent ASD secundum having
 a pattern suggesting autosomal dominant inheritance.
 Secundum defects are often encountered in genetic syndromes such as Holt-Oram,
 Ellis van Creveld, Noonan, Down, Budd-Chiari, and Jarcho-Levine.
 The Holt-Oram syndrome is an autosomal dominant trait, described in 1960,
 characterized by congenital heart disease.
 Often ASD secundum combined with delayed electrical atrio-ventricular conductio
n and forelimb malformations, triphalangeal or hypoplastic thumbs are the
 typical features.
 Modern genetics has shown that the syndrome is result of a mutation in
 the TBX5 gene encoding a transcription factor that controls the α-myosin
 heavy chain.
 A decrease in the α-cardiac actin induces apoptosis and it is thought that
 this would lead to an increased rate of absorption or apoptosis of the
 primary atrial septum thereby causing an atrial septal defect of the secundum
 type.
 In patients with the history of trisomy 21, secundum and primum defects
 are the most frequent lesions
