\begin_layout Subsection
Secundum atrial septal defect (ASD)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It constitutes up to 75-80 % of ASDs a defect within the fossa ovalis usually
 due to one or several defects within septum primum.
 Extension outside the true limits of the fossa ovalis due to a deficiency
 of the infolding of the atrial wall is common.
 It is refered to as secundum defect because of its occurance at the site
 of the embryologic ostium secundum.
 It is large due to deficiencies in the primary atrial septum.
 It is ovular and sometimes extremely irregular in shape.
 Secundum defects with multiple perforations of the membrane in the fossa
 ovalis may also appear.
 Septum secundum is well-formed in most patients.
 Most secundum defects are not confluent with the vena cavae, right pulmonary
 veins, coronary sinus, or the atrioventricular valves.
 With the exception of patent foramen ovale, secundum atrial septal defect
 is a widely known cause of an atrial-level shunt.
 The size of secundum defects ranges from several millimetres to 2–3 cm.
 Larger defects are usually associated with substantial deficiency, or even
 a complete absence of septum primum
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "53_Lutembacher1959,58_Bermudez2007"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Primum atrial septal defect (ASD)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Constitutes up to 15 % of ASDs and it is a partial form of atrio-ventricular
 canal defect (endocardial cushion defect).
 In ASD primum, the atrial septum superior to the AV valves is deficient
 in making the AV valves to insert at the same level, the normal “off-set”
 between the tricuspid and the mitral valve is lacking.
 The defect is furthermore characterized by a common atrioventricular orifice
 containing two distinct atrioventricular valve annuli completed by valve
 tissue adhering to the crest of the ventricular septum.
 The atrioventricular tissue occludes the space that accounts for the ventricula
r septal defect component in the fully complete form of the malformation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "53_Lutembacher1959"

\end_inset

.
 Usually the defect is associated with a cleft in the anterior mitral leaflet
 leading to mitral regurgitation.
 ASD primum is typically linked with a left-axis deviation on the ECG.
 This is due to the arrangement of the conduction tissue and not because
 of a damage of a fascicle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sinus venosus defect
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Constitutes up to 10 % of ASDs and is characterized by a defect in the most
 posterior and superior parts of the atrial septum at the intersection of
 the superior vena cava and the right atrium.
 The superior vena cava overrides the defect and in a majority of cases,
 anomalous right pulmonary vein connection is found.
 Embryologically, this is caused by a persisting interatrial channel in
 the groove between the right and left atria which also wards off a normal
 connection of the right pulmonary veins.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Patent foramen ovale 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is not a true atrial septal defect as there is no absence of tissue.
 The fibromuscular membrane casing the fossa ovalis serves as a flap valve
 permitting right-to-left atrial shunting which is crucial for the foetal
 life.
 After birth, due to the alteration of the interatrial pressure gradient,
 the foramen ovale becomes functionally closed and eventually anatomically
 fused.
 However, in around 25% of the population, the anatomical fusion fails leaving
 a potential for right-to-left shunting when the pressure of the right atrium
 exceeds that of the left atrium.
 However, rare cases have been reported, where there is a stretch of the
 atrial septum due to left heart disease with increased left atrial pressures,
 making a patent foramen ovale to become a true defect and thereby permitting
 left-to-right shunting.
 Considering the embryology of atrial septation, it is not surprising that
 the patency of foramen ovale is usually inhabiting the cranial part of
 the fossa ovalis Figure
