\begin_layout Section
CLINICAL PRESENTATION
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An ASD seldom causes symptoms during childhood, a very large defect may
 allow so much blood flow through, however, and it has been associated with
 frequent respiratory infections, shortness of breath and failure to growth.
 In the adult, symptoms are rare before the age of 40 years but later symptoms
 increase with advancing age, shortness of breath with exertion and palpitations
 due atrial arrhythmias being the most common amongst all symptoms.
 Atrial arrhythmia, resulting from stretching of the conduction system,
 may be the preceding sign of an ASD
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "23_Teteli2014"

\end_inset

.
 Rarely, a patient with ASD will present with stroke or other systemic ischemic
 event caused by paradoxical embolization of thrombus through the defect.
 With persistent right ventricular volume overload or during hypertensive
 pulmonary vascular disease complications in the ASD right ventricular failure
 may cause peripheral oedema, pleural effusion and ascites.
 In the presence of an ASD, there is a potential for paradoxical embolism,
 however, considering the fact that a majority of ASD patients are females,
 many of which undergoing the thrombogenic state of pregnancy, the reports
 on paradoxical embolism are astonishingly rare
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "23_Teteli2014,58_Bermudez2007"

\end_inset

.
 Incidental diagnoses are common by an echocardiogram obtained due to a
 heart murmur or an abnormal finding on a chest radiogram or with an electrocard
iogram’.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Diagnosis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Clinical sign & symptoms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Very careful physical examination consisting of following clinical informations
 : physical appearance, arterial pulse, jugular venous pulse, precordial
 palpation, and auscultation are known to diagnose ASD
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "59_Burn1998"

\end_inset

.
 Upon physical examination, majority of the young patients are without any
 symptoms.
 In around 2/3 there is a constant splitting of the second heart sound as
 a consequence of the right ventricular volume load.
 Signs of right heart failure are rare, but these can be encountered in
 adults with pulmonary hypertension
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "53_Lutembacher1959"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Electrocardiography
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Characteristic electrocardiographic features of atrial septal defect includes
 a tall P wave indicating right atrial enlargement
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "53_Lutembacher1959"

\end_inset

.
 ECG typically shows an “incomplete right bundle branch” pattern along with
 either a right-axis deviation in ostium secundum or a left-axis deviation
 in ostium primum; furthermore a left or low atrial rhythm suggests a sinus
 venosus ASD
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chest X-ray
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A chest X-ray is an essential part of the diagnostic workup in atrial septal
 defect (ASD).
 Typical findings include; heart enlargement (moderate cardiomegaly), particular
ly right atrial enlargement and prominent central pulmonary vasculature
 as a sign of increased pulmonary blood flow.
 Discrepancy between enlarged central pulmonary arteries and relative paucity
 of peripheral vasculature corresponds to pulmonary vascular obstructive
 disease
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "53_Lutembacher1959,59_Burn1998,60_Oeyen2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Echocardiography
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Transthoracic echocardiography is a chief diagnostic tool to determine presence,
 location, size, and haemodynamic characteristics of atrial septal defects.
 Two-dimensional imaging with color Doppler flow mapping depicts the position
 and size of the defect and the direction of flow
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "53_Lutembacher1959,61_Oeyen2010"

\end_inset

.
 Three-dimensional imaging enables enface views about the defect from the
 right and left atrial perspectives, allowing appreciation of the defect’s
 shape and changes in size during the cardiac cycle.
 Transoesophageal echocardiography provides an excellent alternative approach
 in the patients who are presented with obesity, large body habitus, and
 with a history of thoracic surgery
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "53_Lutembacher1959"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Management of congenital heart disease
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Advancement’s in echocardiography have allowed CHDs to be detected as early
 as 17-18 weeks of gestation, and most of which are well tolerated during
 fetal life due its connection with the maternal circulation.
 It is only after birth when that connection is lost.
 Most of the CHDs manifest clinically, some will be incompatible with extra
 uterine life, some clinically apparent within the first few days/weeks
 of life, and others may remain undetected reaching adult life.
 Advances in cardiovascular surgery and intensive care have proved fruitful
 for CHDs correction surgically, and in the future fetal cardiac surgery
 may be a greater possibility for its cure.
 During adulthood, some patients may develop further complications (e.g.
 endocarditis, stroke, systemic or pulmonary hypertension, aortic aneurysm
 or dissection and arrhythmias), and the main causes of their death are
 heart failure and sudden cardiac death.
 Current guidelines emphasize on the surveillance and treatment of adults
 with CHD, with an aim to reduce symptoms, and the risks and severity of
 late complications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Recurrence risks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The process of evaluating and discussing the recurrence risks of disease
 has to take into account the family history and patient characteristics
 (nature of defect and extracardiac manifestations) to further prevent the
 disease.
 For Mendelian patterns of inheritance this is easily predicted, but one
 also has to consider intra- and inter-familial variability.
 The challenges lie in sporadic non-syndromic patients with CHD.
 According to an estimate familial recurrence of CHD represents 3-5% of
 non-syndromic CHD.
 A prospective multicenter study reported recurrent risks of CHD as 4.1%
 (with an affected parent) and 2.1% (with an affected sibling).
 There appeared to be gender differences with a higher prevalence of CHD
 in the offspring of affected women with CHD (5.7%) than those of affected
 men (2.2%).
 The recurrence risk of ASD for a couple after one affected child is ~3%,
 but it increases to 10% if there are two affected children in the family
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "62_Marelli2010"

\end_inset

.
 A population based study of 18,000 Danish patients with CHD estimated an
 individual’s risk of CHD in a family with a history of CHD.
 Furthermore, they found that the relative risk for the same type of CHD
 ranged from 3-fold (septal defects) to 80- fold (heterotaxia) in the first
 degree relatives.
 The overall relative risk for the same type of CHD was 8.15, and for any
 other type of CHD was 2.68, the latter indicating that some families have
 a susceptibility towards acquiring CHD
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "63_Engelen2011,64_Doolittle2013"

\end_inset

.
 As the population of adults with CHD has increased significantly, and these
 adults have had children themselves, clinicians are now foreseeing more
 families with multiple affected individuals with CHD.
 Many of these families were found to have an autosomal dominant inheritance
 pattern, which can significantly increase the risk of CHD to offspring
 (50%).
 Additionally many cases have been reported with families having no apparent
 family history of CHD, but parents have had more than one child with CHD,
 suggesting an autosomal recessive pattern of inheritance (25% recurrence
 risk).
 On the contrary, there is a great variability in the phenotype between
 individuals from the same family.
 These familial recurrences of CHD are a significant resource for molecular
 studies and for the further identification of genes involved in heart developme
nt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Clinical genetics and gene identification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Genetic counselling in patients with congenital heart disease
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The human body comprises of more than ten trillion cells belonging to over
 200 different cell types.
 All of these cells, with only few exceptions like erythrocyte and B cells,
 contain common genetic information.
 a Phenotypic variability is a highly regulated process; the expression
 of genes, i.e.
 the synthesis of a functional gene product based on DNA information, is
 a highly regulated process.
 This regulation is vital for processes like; development, differentiation,
 regeneration, signaling and normal organ function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "67_Loewe2008,69_Yates2012"

\end_inset

.
 It is crucial to identify the underlying genetic factor in a patient with
 CHD as there may be: (a) other organ system involvement, (b) prognostic
 information for clinical outcome, (c) important genetic reproductive risks
 for the family, and (d) other family members for whom genetic testing may
 be appropriate.
 With the mainstreaming of clinical genetics services and an increased awareness
 amongst other medical professionals, a great number of patients and families
 with CHD are seen by clinical genetics departments for genetic counseling.
 For many of the patients, the technique of genetic counselling helps to:
 (a) identify and understand the genetic basis of their CHD, (b) provide
 accurate genetic counselling on recurrence risks, and (c) identify and
 manage extracardiac manifestations.
 Although, the majority of the cases has an isolated anomaly and is sporadic,
 some will be syndromic and/or familial, and this will in turn affect the
 nature of genetic counselling for these individuals.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "65_Niu2013,66_Eddy2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Human Genome
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DNA is centralized in the cell nucleus and is organized in 23 pairs of homologou
s chromosomes in almost each cells of the human body.
 Chromosomes consist of chromatin; DNA folded with histone and non-histone
 proteins, and further enables the condensation of the DNA in the nucleus.
 In addition to this, they play a pivotal role in regulatory processes.
 Adding more to this, the chromosomal DNA, a very small portion of the genetic
 information is coded in the mitochondrial genome.
 The DNA is organized in a double helix, in which the four nucleobases adenine
 (A), guanine (G), thymine (T) and cytosine (C) are bound by hydrogen bonds
 in pairs of complementary bases (A and T, G and C).
 Ultimately, they code the information for the transcription of ribonucleic
 acid (RNA) molecules and are then translated into proteins.
 In 1958, Francis Crick formulated this flow of genetic information as the
 “Central Dogma of Molecular Biology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In total, the human genome consists of approximately 3,200 megabases and
 contains about 25,000 protein-coding genes, which correspond to only 1-2%
 of its total size.
 Besides regulatory elements such as promoters or enhancers, a vast majority
 of the non-coding portion of the genome has long been considered as “junk
 DNA” serving no specific biological function.
 However, recent studies like the Encyclopedia of DNA Elements (ENCODE)
 project, which assigned biochemical function to 80% of the human genome16,
 gave rise to a lively debate about the nature of non-coding DNA and the
 definition of biological function, which will have to be refined in the
 upcoming future
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "67_Loewe2008,69_Yates2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Genetic Assessment of proband
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assessment of any patient with a condition suspected to have a genetic
 basis always starts with a detailed family history spanning preceeding
 at least three generations, including the presence of consanguinity.
 This allows the identification of any Mendelian patterns of inheritance.
 A detailed history and clinical examination will help to identify features
 predicting the underlying genetic syndrome with CHD (e.g.
 developmental delay, learning difficulties, extracardiac manifestations,
 behavioural problems, and facial dysmorphism).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mutations and Genetic Variation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Genetic differences among individuals are described as genetic variation,
 which is created by recombination and mutations.
 While mutations provide the material for natural selection and are the
 primary source of diversity among species, they often damage normal biological
 functions and are proved to be harmful for the individual
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "70_Haraksingh2013,71_Bhangale2005"

\end_inset

.
 They can come into existence from a variety of causes including; errors
 in recombination or chromosome segregation during meiosis, errors in DNA
 replication, mobile DNA elements, DNA damage through mutagenic agents and
 spontaneous deamination of methylated CpG dinucleotides.
 Only the mutations present in germ line cells are transmitted to the next
 generation; yet, somatic mutations can be the cause for a variety of diseases
 like cancer
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "72_Stankiewicz2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mutations are classified based on their size, biochemical nature and functional
 effect.
 Single nucleotide variations (SNVs) only change one nucleotide and it can
 be of following types; silent, missense (altering the protein’s amino acid
 sequence) or nonsense (coding for a translation stop).
 Missense mutations can be devastating to the protein’s function or can
 be benign, e.g.
 when the amino acid is exchanged for a functionally conserved residue.
 Besides coding regions, SNVs can also influence regulatory elements like
 promoters, enhancers, transcription factor binding sites or splice junctions
 as well as ncRNAs, thus potentially affecting regulatory mechanisms.
 Profoundly common SNVs with a population frequency of ≥1% are denoted as
 single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs).
 The second class of local variations are short insertions or deletions
 with a length ranging from only a few base pairs (usually <5bp), which
 are referred to as InDels.
 They can prove to be potentially very harmful by altering the reading frame
 of coding sequences.
 Moreover, only InDels of triplets will keep the reading frame intact.
 However, they still are able to alter the amino acid sequence of the resulting
 protein
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "73_Zhang2009,74_Nagaoka2012"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Copy number variations (CNVs) are submicroscopic structural variations that
 alter the copy number of entire genes or genomic regions.
 CNVs can result in Mendelian diseases or complex sporadic syndromes by
 various molecular mechanisms, including; altered gene dosage, gene fusion,
 gene disruption and position effects.
 However, they can also be found as benign polymorphic variations[75, 76].Conclus
ively, numerical chromosomal abnormalities (aneuploidies) like monosomies
 or trisomies represent a major mutational threat and are the leading cause
 for miscarriages and congenital defects in human.
 Most of the aneuploidies are lethal during embryonic development; others
 may cause severe syndromic disorders affecting multiple organ systems.
 The identification of trisomy 21 as the cause for Down syndrome in 1959,
 provided the first link between a chromosome abnormality and a clinical
 disorder[77, 78].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
WHOLE EXOME SEQUENCING
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whole exome sequencing (WES) is a technique used to identify and sequence
 the coding regions of all annotated protein coding genes.
 It can be further divided into three parts: preparation of genomic DNA
 libraries, hybridization of these libraries, and sequencing of the hybridized
 fragments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are some pitfalls in using whole exome sequencing instead of whole
 genome sequencing.
 Since, whole exome sequencing only identifies the sequence of the coding
 regions many structural and other functional parts are not being included
 which may also contribute for the occurrence of a disease.
 WES does not cover untranslated regions, enhancers, and long-noncoding
 RNAs, which may be potentially functional and helpful in diagnosing various
 diseases.
 Structural variations such as ; the copy number variants, translocations,
 and inversions are also not included in whole exome sequencing.
 Despite these downfalls, whole exome sequencing is still broadly used among
 researchers due to its cost effectiveness, robustness, and timeliness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When compared to whole genome sequencing, WES costs five times less, has
 a higher coverage depth of 100x versus 30x, and requires a short processing
 time since only a sixth of the genome is used for the analysis.
 Additionally, most allelic variants that have been found to be main reason
 behind the Mendelian disorders disrupting protein-coding sequences, which
 can easily be detected via exome sequencing.
 Variants in the exome sequences also have a larger effect size rather than
 those within non-coding sequences even in highly conserved regions.
 Henceforth, considering all these reasons our lab has chosen to perform
 whole exome sequencing on the mutant mice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
EVOLUTIONARY CONSERVATION
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Evolutionary conservation is crucial in providing support for genes that
 may contribute to disease.
 Conservation means that the amino acids at a certain position are the same
 throughout a set of species.
 Mutations in regions that are highly conserved are more likely to result
 in a disease than those that are less conserved or not conserved at all.
 It has been reported as a basic criterion for examining the disease causing
 potential of an amino acid or nucleotide sequence change.
 Research done by Pierpont et al.
 describes three criteria used to establish the disease causing potential
 of a mutation.
 These criteria include: a sequence change that alters the gene coding sense,
 gene splice site, or regulatory region of the protein; segregates with
 disease in a kindred; and is not found in unrelated, unaffected control
 chromosomes.
 Some mutations may also be considered as conserved if the changed in the
 amino acid residue has similar properties of the original residue.
 Comparisons of the sequences of the same protein in different species helped
 researchers to pinpoint those residues that are structurally or functionally
 vital as these are conserved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mutations may be tolerated or considered nonthreatening, as long as the
 change does not destroy or seriously alter the protein’s function.
 Mutations are damaging, or threatening, when there are changes in side
 chains that are involved in binding substrates or cofactors, that interact
 with other proteins, or that participate in catalytic mechanisms altering
 or wrecking the protein’s function.
 
\end_layout

